{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642327"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:37:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:37:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17930"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17930"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.18,0.16,0,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10644"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77513"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10644"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63025"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24796"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77513"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive shortness of breath and fatigue. She has a medical history of type 2 Diabetes Mellitus and obesity. She does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiac examination reveals a displaced apex beat and a third heart sound. An echocardiogram shows reduced ejection fraction and left ventricular dilation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely precipitating event for her cardiomyopathy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Systolic dysfunction","Diastolic dysfunction","Cardiac hypertrophy","Pulmonary hypertension","Adipositas cordis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and echocardiographic findings consistent with a dilated cardiomyopathy, which is often associated with metabolic diseases such as diabetes and obesity. The echocardiogram shows reduced ejection fraction and left ventricular dilation, indicating \u003Cstrong\u003Esystolic dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E. Systolic dysfunction refers to the heart\u0027s impaired ability to contract and pump blood effectively, leading to symptoms of heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiastolic dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E involves impaired relaxation and filling of the heart, which can also occur in metabolic conditions but is not the primary issue in this case, given the reduced ejection fraction and dilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E refers to thickening of the heart muscle, which occurs in response to chronic pressure overload, such as hypertension, but is not the primary finding here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is increased blood pressure in the pulmonary arteries and is not directly related to the findings of systolic dysfunction and left ventricular dilation in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdipositas cordis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to fatty infiltration of the heart, which can occur in obesity, but the primary issue here is the systolic dysfunction leading to dilated cardiomyopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metabolic diseases can lead to cardiomyopathy through various mechanisms, including systolic and diastolic dysfunction.","Systolic dysfunction is often a result of impaired contractility of the heart muscle, commonly seen in metabolic cardiomyopathies.","Diastolic dysfunction involves impaired relaxation and filling of the heart, which can also occur in metabolic conditions."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press.","Isfort, M., Stevens, S. C., Schaffer, S., Jong, C. J., \u0026 Wold, L. E. (2014). Metabolic dysfunction in diabetic cardiomyopathy. Heart failure reviews, 19, 35-48.","ISO 690","Maack C, Murphy E. Metabolic cardiomyopathies - fighting the next epidemic. Cardiovasc Res. 2017 Mar 15;113(4):367-369. doi: 10.1093/cvr/cvx022. Epub 2017 Feb 16. PMID: 28203832; PMCID: PMC5852643.","Guertl B, Noehammer C, Hoefler G. Metabolic cardiomyopathies. Int J Exp Pathol. 2000 Dec;81(6):349-72. doi: 10.1046/j.1365-2613.2000.00186.x. PMID: 11298185; PMCID: PMC2517748."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63025"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17930"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63025"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T10:48:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T10:49:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10644"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77513"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"me